MODIFICATIONS APPLIED DURING PORT
----------------------------------------------------------------------

  * Restricted scope to the franz-go (kgo) consumer and producer. The
    sarama variant, the Redpanda-specific input/output/cache wrappers,
    the schema-registry input/output, and the AWS MSK IAM helpers were
    not ported.

  * Removed all dependencies on
    github.com/redpanda-data/benthos/v4/public/service. The Benthos
    Message / MessageBatch / AckFunc / Resources / ConfigField surface
    was replaced with package-local interfaces (ConsumerI, ProducerI,
    BatchI, AckFnI, RecordEnvelopeI). Configuration moved from
    service.ParsedConfig to plain Go option structs.

  * Refactored to the boxer coding standards (see CODINGSTANDARDS.md
    in github.com/stergiotis/boxer): receiver naming convention,
    interface suffix "I", enum suffix "E", named return values,
    error builder usage (eh.Errorf / eb.Build), sized integer fields
    on structs, compile-time interface assertions.

  * Replaced the service.Logger adapter with zerolog.

  * Replaced github.com/Jeffail/shutdown lifecycle helpers with
    context-cancellation primitives where the simplification was
    safe; otherwise retained the dependency.

  * Did not port the
    github.com/redpanda-data/connect/internal/impl/kafka/enterprise/
    subdirectory, which is licensed under the Redpanda Community
    License (RCL), not Apache-2.0.

  * Did not port scram.go. The XDGSCRAMClient type wraps
    github.com/xdg-go/scram for the sarama path; the franz-go path
    uses github.com/twmb/franz-go/pkg/sasl/scram natively, so the
    wrapper is unnecessary in this port.

  * Dropped the AWS_MSK_IAM and REDPANDA_CLOUD_SERVICE_ACCOUNT SASL
    mechanisms from sasl.go. AWS_MSK_IAM is supplied upstream via an
    indirect plug-point (AWSSASLFromConfigFn) populated when
    components/aws is imported; pebble2impl does not import that
    layer. REDPANDA_CLOUD_SERVICE_ACCOUNT depends on
    github.com/redpanda-data/connect/v4/internal/serviceaccount,
    a Connect-internal package not exposed for re-use. The four
    portable franz-go mechanisms (PLAIN, OAUTHBEARER, SCRAM-SHA-256,
    SCRAM-SHA-512) remain.

  * Dropped AddHeaders and ExtractHeaders from franz_headers.go (and
    the kafkaHeaders metadata-key constant they shared). Those
    functions converted between []kgo.RecordHeader and
    service.Message metadata; this port exposes *kgo.Record directly
    to application code, so the conversion is unneeded. The pure
    helpers GetHeaderValue and SetHeaderValue were retained.

  * franz_reader_ordered.go: dropped the per-message
    dispatch.CtxOnTriggerSignal mechanism. Upstream used the trigger
    to clear pendingDispatch[batchID] when the Benthos pipeline took
    a batch's records into the processor chain (i.e. before ack),
    enabling pipelined throughput on a single partition. This port
    has no processor-chain notion, so pendingDispatch[batchID] is
    set on pop and cleared only on ack, yielding strictly serial
    batches per partition. Applications that want pipelined
    throughput can wrap Read into a producer/consumer goroutine pair
    externally. The companion test (TestPartitionCacheOrdering),
    which existed solely to exercise the dispatch trigger under
    tangled multi-worker dispatch, was dropped as well; the
    chunking-focused TestPartitionCacheBatching was retained.

  * franz_reader_ordered.go: dropped the ConsumerLag wiring (the
    kafka_lag per-message metadata, the lag-refresh goroutine, and
    the redpanda_lag gauge metric). Phase 8 may re-introduce
    consumer-lag observability via a metrics seam.

  * franz_reader_ordered.go: dropped ConnectionTest. NewFranzClient
    already calls Ping on construction; callers that want a
    "test connection" path can call NewFranzClient + Close.

  * franz_reader_unordered.go: dropped the service.Batcher
    integration. Upstream's partitionTracker held a service.Batcher
    per partition and a dedicated goroutine driving size-based and
    time-based batch flushes. This port emits one *kgo.Record per
    Batch (single-record batches), simplifying partitionTracker to a
    checkpointer + lock with no internal goroutine. Applications
    that want size or time batching wrap Read in their own batcher
    externally.

  * franz_reader_unordered.go: dropped the franzRecordToMsgFn
    indirection (which defaulted to FranzRecordToMessageV0 / V1
    depending on the multi-header config flag) and the multi_header
    field. *kgo.Record is exposed directly per ADR-0015 /
    EXPLANATION.md; callers read record.Headers themselves.

  * franz_reader_unordered.go: dropped ConsumerLag wiring and
    ConnectionTest (same scope decisions as the ordered reader).
    Upstream's "Deprecated: use toggled" markers on the config-DSL
    helpers do not carry over: the deprecation targeted those
    helpers (which are dropped here anyway), not the
    FranzReaderUnordered struct itself, which the toggled wrapper
    composes rather than supersedes.

  * franz_reader_toggled.go: dropped the entire Benthos config-DSL
    surface (krtField* constants, FranzReaderToggledConfigFields,
    NewFranzReaderToggledFromConfig). Upstream's "toggled" wrapper
    existed primarily to expose a single YAML schema that switched
    between ordered and unordered via a nested
    `unordered_processing.enabled` flag. Without YAML config, the
    wrapper reduces to a constructor that picks the underlying
    reader from a Go-struct field; the upstream return type
    service.BatchInput is replaced with the package-local
    ConsumerI.

